C_IBk7Mtzg__ZBsQWKJVDX-FA_48PjxsUpenNJ9N3iMysTa067K64MkU_nrdhGM7n0IoYqovWMqGnqst-tnirR-MlUMBhOXFa3aEYfoe5Aj0qROcdC9pc9HyNyqTGyPQjSUALliIK66Y8Q8MdpYukZppLSWexMMU53UViyIF6BWSjJOI11LI7yx2eOdFlg1ZuehwaCpJPnrRcQzSTRBxCny_2oZ-HbmtgVDfI5-u0lsotXLjU-Z2JBDIl8c\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test configurations**\\n\\nI'm thinking about using only one test version, version 1 with jmdns 0.2 for the test implementation, and not including 3.5.7. This would help cover remaining lines, especially around the NoSuchMethod issue. However, this would also mean losing the version 3 create/build call sites. I wonder if it’s better to keep both versions. Perhaps I can set up Gradle’s forkEvery = 1 in the build.gradle file to avoid port conflicts, since that controls the forking per test class, not method.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring test structure options**\\n\\nI’m considering whether I can split both methods into separate test classes for one-to-one mapping, since the rule suggests keeping coverage for each dynamic-access class in its own dedicated Java test file. However, I'm unsure if I can actually separate them. I could configure JUnit to use @TestMethodOrder, running version 1 first, but it would still run in the same JVM. Maybe I could set one test method for version 1 to run first and then close it using reflection.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing JmDNS behavior**\\n\\nI think I can instantiate JmDNS v1 with a non-loopback interface, but it still binds to port 5353. The issue may not be with the port itself but rather the hostname. I want to confirm if StatusLogger isn’t showing properly. The duration for v1 seems to be 0.073 seconds compared to version 3 taking 2 seconds. It's unclear if the tests completed would show the order correctly. I need to ensure that v1's constructor doesn’t rely on a local host by adjusting the hosts file through a JVM argument when launching.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Planning Gradle implementation**\\n\\nI’m considering adding a Gradle system property for HOSTS_FILE. To compute the file before the Test task runs, Gradle can write the hosts file using the doFirst method with NetworkInterface, although it involves Groovy. However, the jdk.net.hosts.file system property needs to be passed at JVM startup to ensure InetAddress utilizes it right from the beginning. I think implementing Gradle to create the file is a good plan. After that, I might remove the @BeforeAll annotation.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_fxLrWKKeF4yzapowQ4u7pqJb|fc_049dae7f6ec59baf016a0d8d97b8a48193bc49402273c6924d", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "python3 - <<'PY'\nimport urllib.request, json, urllib.parse\nq=urllib.parse.quote('g:jmdns OR g:javax.jmdns OR a:jmdns')\nurl='https://search.maven.org/solrsearch/select?q='+q+'&rows=100&wt=json'\nprint(url)\ndata=json.load(urllib.request.urlopen(url,timeout=10))\nfor doc in data['response']['docs']:\n print(doc.get('g'), doc.get('a'), doc.get('latestVersion'), doc.get('versionCount'))\nPY", "timeout": 15}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2848, "output": 2143, "cacheRead": 61440, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 66431, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779273081398, "responseId": "resp_049dae7f6ec59baf016a0d8d7a1ee88193be1814b40f958242"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_fxLrWKKeF4yzapowQ4u7pqJb|fc_049dae7f6ec59baf016a0d8d97b8a48193bc49402273c6924d", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "https://search.maven.org/solrsearch/select?q=g%3Ajmdns%20OR%20g%3Ajavax.jmdns%20OR%20a%3Ajmdns&rows=100&wt=json\njavax.jmdns jmdns 3.4.1 3\njmdns jmdns 1.0 2\norg.jmdns jmdns 3.6.1 14\ncom.github.rickyclarkson jmdns 3.4.2-r353-1 1\norg.jvnet.hudson jmdns 3.2.1-hudson-1 4\norg.eclipse.ecf.provider jmdns 1.0.0-v20070627-1030 1\nactivemq jmdns 1.0-RC2 1\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1779273112763}]}
